Together with the serial number, the prefix/namespace provides the specimen ID.

Specimen ID: An identifier for the Organism instance (as opposed to a particular digital record of the Organism). May be a globally unique identifier (GUID) or an identifier specific to the data set.

Examples: 
"U.amer.44"; "Smedley"; "Orca J 23", but could also be a URI referring to this particular specimen.

Darwin Core current standard
An identifier for an individual or named group of individual organisms represented in the Occurrence. Meant to accommodate resampling of the same individual or group for monitoring purposes. May be a GUID or an identifier specific to a data set. In the absence of a persistent GUID, construct one from a combination of identifiers in the record that will most closely make the GUID globally unique and persistent. "[InstitutionCode]: [CollectionCode]: [CatalogNumber]"

Provide institution and collection code in the first and the catalog number in the second input field.

Examples: 
urn:lsid:nhm.ku.edu:Herps:32
"FMNH:Mammal:145732"

Details: http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/history/index.htm#individualID-2009-04-24

By setting the toggle button to "red=blocked", all information within the surrounding red box will not be visible to any other user except for the creator of this entry. 

Blocking location information can be necessary when for instance providing information about a sampling location that is not appropriate for world-wide release. Please block that information for endangered or protected specimen or provide only non-specific information (e.g. only the country, but not the exact area within the country)
Please provide information about why you have blocked the location information.

Please select the biome in which this location is located in. This input field has an autocomplete function, which allows you to start typing the label or the resource of the biome and the application will suggest you a list of matching hits from which you can select.

[From Environment Ontology Annotation Guidelines: EnvO's biome class and its subclasses are intended to identify the ecosystem in which an entity of interest is embedded (i.e. the entity is a component of that system). In order for an ecosystem to qualify as a biome, ecological communities (or representatives thereof) resident in an ecosystem must have evolved adaptations to that ecosystem. Thus, biomes possess an evolutionarily consequential degree of temporal and spatial stability. Currently, instances of EnvO's biome class (or its subclasses) are not dependent on spatial or temporal scale.]

Please select the biome in which this location is located in. This search button will re-direct you to a search interface in which you can search for the respective biomes.

SPRO_0000000069.SPRO_0000000820:
Darwin Core Standard
A brief phrase or a standard term ("cf.", "aff.") to express the determiner's doubts about the Identification.

Examples: 1) For the determination "Quercus aff. agrifolia var. oxyadenia", identificationQualifier would be "aff. agrifolia var. oxyadenia" with accompanying values "Quercus" in genus, "agrifolia" in specificEpithet, "oxyadenia" in infraspecificEpithet, and "var." in rank. 2) For the determination "Quercus agrifolia cf. var. oxyadenia", identificationQualifier would be "cf. var. oxyadenia " with accompanying values "Quercus" in genus, "agrifolia" in specificEpithet, "oxyadenia" in infraspecificEpithet, and "var." in rank.

Details: http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/history/#identificationQualifier-2009-04-24
